<paragraph start="9" end="11">
<Alignment>1</Alignment>
<content start="9" end="10">
<component><class>org.concord.modeler.PageTextBox</class>
<width>750.0</width>
<height>150.0</height>
<title>&lt;html&gt;
  &lt;head&gt;
    
  &lt;/head&gt;
  &lt;body face=&quot;verdana&quot;&gt;
    There are plenty of electrons in a conductor that are not tightly bound to 
    atoms. They are in constant random motion, like the molecules of a gas. In 
    the absence of an external electric field, there is no net flow--the 
    number of electrons that move in one direction equals approximately the 
    number of electrons that move in the opposite direction. When an electric 
    field is applied, however, the number of electrons that move against (&lt;a href=&quot;script:page:0:message &lt;t&gt;&lt;font face=verdana&gt;The direction of an electric field is defined as the direction in which&lt;br&gt;the electric force on a &lt;b&gt;positive&lt;/b&gt; charge points.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;However, an electron carries a &lt;b&gt;negative&lt;/b&gt; charge. So, the electric force &lt;br&gt;on it points to the opposite direction of the field.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/t&gt;&quot;&gt;why 
    against?&lt;/a&gt;) the direction of the field is greater than the number of 
    electrons that move along the direction of the field. As a result, the 
    electrons generally &lt;b&gt;drift&lt;/b&gt; against the direction of the field.
  &lt;/body&gt;
&lt;/html&gt;
</title>
<opaque>false</opaque>
</component></content>

