<component><class>org.concord.modeler.PageTextBox</class>
<width>750.0</width>
<height>150.0</height>
<title>&lt;html&gt;
  &lt;head&gt;
    
  &lt;/head&gt;
  &lt;body marginwidth=&quot;5&quot; face=&quot;verdana&quot; marginheight=&quot;5&quot;&gt;
    &lt;strong&gt;Advanced&lt;/strong&gt;: The above picture of electron movement in 
    conductors is called &lt;b&gt;the Drude model&lt;/b&gt;, which is a good explanation 
    of electric conduction. However, it is not very accurate. The modern 
    picture of electric conduction does not view electrons as tiny particles. 
    Instead, electrons are treated as quantum probability waves that propogate 
    through crystal lattices. The resistance originates from the interactions 
    between electron waves and lattice vibrations--not from bouncing off atoms 
    as depicted in the Drude model. This picture will be important in 
    understanding superconductivity.
  &lt;/body&gt;
&lt;/html&gt;
</title>
<bgcolor>-111112</bgcolor>
<border>Raised Bevel</border>
</component></content>

